---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import DocsShell from '~/components/widgets/DocsShell.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Skills — Aitroop Docs',
};

const skills = [
  { name: 'github-mcp',     desc: 'Read repos, list commits, fetch PRs, open issues — all GitHub operations the agent might need.' },
  { name: 'lead-finder',    desc: 'Find people matching an ICP across LinkedIn, Crunchbase, and company sites. Returns name, role, company, contact.' },
  { name: 'web-scrape',     desc: 'Fetch and parse any public web page. Handles JS-rendered content, returns clean text or structured data.' },
  { name: 'seo-audit',      desc: 'Run an SEO audit on a URL — meta tags, page speed, structured data, broken links, ranking opportunities.' },
  { name: 'gmail-search',   desc: 'Search your Gmail (requires Gmail Connect). Returns matching threads with subjects, senders, dates, snippets.' },
  { name: 'calendar-mcp',   desc: 'Query and create calendar events. Find conflicts, schedule meetings, summarize the week ahead.' },
  { name: 'crm-sync',       desc: 'Read and write Salesforce / HubSpot records. Used by Apps that update CRM state based on agent reasoning.' },
  { name: 'csv-tools',      desc: 'Slice, filter, group, and aggregate CSV files. The agent can do most of this directly, but csv-tools is faster and deterministic on large files.' },
  { name: 'pdf-extract',    desc: 'Pull text, tables, and metadata out of a PDF — including scanned PDFs via OCR.' },
  { name: 'image-gen',      desc: 'Generate images from text prompts. Useful for slide decks, marketing assets, social media drafts.' },
];
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <DocsShell current="skills">
    <h1>Skills</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Skills are reusable capability modules the agent can call. They're how the agent does things beyond
      "just talk to me" — fetch pages, search emails, extract PDFs, query CRMs, generate images.
    </p>

    <h2>How skills work</h2>
    <p>
      You install a Skill once. From that moment on, every Chat and every App in your workspace can use it.
      You don't have to mention the Skill by name in your prompt — the agent decides which Skills to call
      based on the task.
    </p>
    <p>
      Skills are just tools. When the agent calls one, you see the call inline in the conversation: the
      tool name, the arguments, and the result. If anything looks wrong, you can call it out and the
      agent will adjust.
    </p>

    <h2>Installing a skill</h2>
    <p>
      From the dashboard, open <strong>Skills → Library</strong>. Browse, search, or filter by category.
      Click <strong>Install</strong> on any Skill to add it to your workspace.
    </p>
    <p>
      Some Skills require a Connect. For example, <code>gmail-search</code> needs the Gmail Connect to be
      authorized. The Skill page tells you what's needed; the install flow walks you through any missing
      authorizations.
    </p>

    <h2>A sample of available skills</h2>
    <p>
      The library has 150+ Skills today and is growing. A representative slice:
    </p>
    <div class="not-prose mt-3 mb-2" style="max-width:720px;">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)] divide-y divide-[var(--aw-color-border)]">
        {skills.map((s) => (
          <div class="p-4 flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-3 sm:items-start">
            <div class="shrink-0 sm:w-44">
              <code class="text-[0.8125rem] font-mono text-primary">{s.name}</code>
            </div>
            <p class="text-[0.875rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-muted)] leading-[1.6] m-0">{s.desc}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Scoping skills per stage</h2>
    <p>
      In Chat, all installed Skills are available. In a saved App, each Stage declares which Skills it
      can use. Restricting the Skill set on a Stage has two upsides:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Predictability.</strong> The agent can only do things you've explicitly allowed. The behavior of the App stays stable as it's re-run by different teammates.</li>
      <li><strong>Speed.</strong> Fewer tools means less reasoning about which tool to use. Stages that need only one or two Skills run noticeably faster.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Set this in the App editor under <strong>Stages → Skills</strong>. By default, an App inherits the
      Skill set that was active in the original chat.
    </p>

    <h2>Permissions and side effects</h2>
    <p>
      Some Skills only read (<code>gmail-search</code>, <code>web-scrape</code>). Others can write
      (<code>crm-sync</code>, <code>calendar-mcp</code> when creating events). Write-capable Skills
      are clearly marked in the library. The first time an App is set up to use a write-capable
      Skill, the platform asks you to confirm.
    </p>
    <p>
      Scheduled runs of an App will not silently start writing if you didn't authorize writes when you
      built it. You will be asked explicitly.
    </p>

    <h2>Building your own skill</h2>
    <p>
      Custom Skills are on the roadmap and available in early access — get in touch via
      <a href="/contact">contact</a> if you want to define a Skill for your own internal tools.
      For now, the library covers the common cases, and most teams find they don't need custom Skills
      until they're well into production use.
    </p>

    <div class="next-up">
      <span class="label">Next</span>
      <a href="/docs/connects">Connects — OAuth integrations</a>
    </div>
  </DocsShell>
</Layout>
